s of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe imaginaries of northern landscape have not remained static in the era of ecological crisis but play a pivotal function within the geopolitics of visual representation. Such imaginaries can sanction those dominant discourses that frame environmental catastrophe as the consequence of undifferentiated human activity, but, it is argued, they also have the capacity to represent a complexity and heterogeneity frequently absent from this broad discursive field. The contributors to this volume engage with the practice, curation and utilization of photography and other lens-based media, to examine the critical role of visual culture in shaping and interrogating conceptions of environmental catastrophe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aArt History. 4aArt. 4aClimate. 4aFine Arts. 4aGeopolitics. 4aHuman Ecology. 4aImage. 4aLandscape. 4aNature. 4aNorthern. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh  aArt History.  aArt.  aClimate.  aFine Arts.  aGeopolitics.  aHuman Ecology.  aImage.  aLandscape.  aNature.  aNorthern.1 aBartlett, Flora Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrenzel, Janna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldie, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHartle, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvard, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Aileen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyvönen, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/